In this document we are going to take a look at the voting patterns of the United Nations General Assembly. The data that we are going to use is from the unvotes package. There are additional packages that we will make use of to do our data analysis. These packages are loaded below in what is called an R code chunk:

library("unvotes")
library("tidyverse")
library("lubridate")
library("DT")

Analysis

Letâs make a cool visualization!! I am interested in how often certain countries voted âYesâ on a resolution each year. First, letâs pick the countries we are interested in showing.

countries <- c("United States of America", "Italy", "Russian Federation", "Cuba")

Letâs make a plot (and do some work to get there)!

un_votes %>%
  filter(country %in% countries) %>%
  inner_join(un_roll_calls, by = "rcid") %>%
  group_by(year = year(date), country) %>%
  summarize(
    votes = n(),
    percent_yes = mean(vote == "yes")
    ) %>%
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = year, y = percent_yes, color = country)) +
    geom_line() +
    labs(
      title = "Percentage of 'Yes' votes in the UN General Assembly",
      subtitle = "1946 to 2015",
      y = "% Yes",
      x = "Year",
      color = "Country"
    )

Now letâs take a look at how the voting behaviors have changed per year for each of the issues. We will look at the United States and Russia. Hereâs the plot and the work to get to it!

un_votes %>%
  filter(country %in% c("United States of America", "Russian Federation")) %>%
  inner_join(un_roll_calls, by = "rcid") %>%
  inner_join(un_roll_call_issues, by = "rcid") %>%
  group_by(country, year = year(date), issue) %>%
  summarize(
    votes = n(),
    percent_yes = mean(vote == "yes")
    ) %>%
  filter(votes > 5) %>%  # only use records where there are more than 5 votes
  ggplot(mapping = aes(x = year, y = percent_yes, color = country)) +
    geom_point() +
    geom_smooth(method = "loess", se = FALSE) +
    facet_wrap(~ issue) +
    labs(
      title = "Percentage of 'Yes' votes in the UN General Assembly",
      subtitle = "1946 to 2015",
      y = "% Yes",
      x = "Year",
      color = "Country"
    )

This analysis is a good example of code that can be easily altered to tell a totally different story. You just need to change which countries are being filtered.
